reviewText: I enjoy this weekly series.  It is a team of FBI agents who are called to various sections of the country to solve significant murder cases, especially serial murder cases.  I like all the characters, especially Garcia the computer hacking whiz FBI agent.  Joe Mantegna replaced Mandy Patinkin and it works for me.  Both are strong actors and easily made themselves stand out in the cast.  I also like the stiff FBI head agent, Hodge, the young genius PHD and the black male agent. The two other women have the least effect on me and I can't say I'd really miss either of them.  I think this series may have too many characters so it really makes these two superfluous.  I'd eliminate them. All the stories were good this season and the season closer was especially strong.  It was quite gruesome and probably their very worst case. The reason this doesn't reach five stars is that the British do this same type of show but they do it better.  This is because they go for reality over the sentimental and the moralistic. Watch WIRE IN THE BLOOD from the UK and compare it to this show.  Right away you can spot just how much grittier and realistic the UK show is. An American series, and this is a prime example of one, always has more of a Disney patina to it regardless of which studio made the series. We in America rarely can resist adding schmaltz, sentimentality and morals to our tv series. The British are made of sterner stuff, as they say.
summary: Enjoyable But Could Learn from British Series

FYI - I have no idea why but using the same red, white and yellow cables, I finally got closed captioning when I switched out my multi-region Opppo DVD player for my cheapo Philips VCR/DVD combo that I got at Target a year ago.I suggest experimenting with the video plug in as many outlets on the tv set as it will fit to find closed captioning.  I am using a more than ten year old big box tv set and a newer but cheapo VCR/DVD to get cc.  I also get cc from my twenty plus year old VCRs.Lo Fi is the season finale for Season 3 while the conclusion is the season premiere for Season 4.  This is a problem if you only want to buy one season but I like both Seasons 3 and 4.  The thought-provoking Lo-Fi two-parter makes a great starting point for introducing the series to the uninitiated.  Reid's facial tics have distilled to be tolerable and Prentiss's throwaway snark seems to have increased in Season 4.  In the episode after their NYC adventure, Joe Mantegna encourages Thomas Gibson's character to explore the "pretty byways" of Middle America.  Three episodes later, we get the "Paradise" episode.  This show is really funny in subtle ways despite the overuse of banter in the dialogue.  Keep an eye out for Adam Lincoln (as in ABRAHAM) playing a front desk clerk in the penultimate episode of the season.  This is the season I would buy but unfortunately domestic versions of the show don't have subtitles and I hate the way closed captions jump around the screen on broadcast episodes.  Subtitles should run in a black bar beneath the picture.  I haven't been able to get closed captioning on these dvds though.
summary: Closed Captioning comes through on a VCR/DVD machine

reviewText: As we all know Prentiss comes and goes because of her "other job" so we won't see much of her in this season.  J.J. is back in full, thank the Lord, and this pretty much is like all other seasons, excellent.  While there is no real REAPER type character in this season, you get a TON of episodes, far more than 99% of good shows out there (2X-3X the amount of Dexter season episodes) and almost all are well written.You just have to own all the seasons of this show.  If you like SVU you will realize how much you missed out wasting your time watching that show over this - and I was a SUV addict.  Far better acting, far more interesting shows, but the only downside is the CLEARANCE RATE.The one thing I have always disliked about Criminal Minds is how many UNSUBS they catch, and quickly.  The odds of solving a homicide are about 60% nationwide.  Additionally, the BAU or BSU of the FBI does not handle half the cases they actually depict here.  Sure they give the obligatory "we've been invited" tagline, but most jurisdictions do not want the FBI handling their cases, especially within 24 hours."Wheels up in Thirty" - as a former federal investigator, I can assure you that they do not have a private jet, they fly coach - and cheap.  The FBI does not have a private landing strip for the BAU and to have a plane ready, with pilot and gas at the ready, would be impossible.  At best they arrive next day.  They never show anyone packing, just the stuff on their backs???But those nit picky things aside, great show and it will me missed when off the air.  The X-Files of the 2000's.

Of the four seasons, this season may be the best.  With more dark storylines, the series follow Rossi, Hotchner, Prentiss, Morgan, Reid, Jareau, and Garcia as they deal with the evil side of human nature and more of their own personal stories, connections, and demons.The fourth season fleshes out these characters and their interdependence on each other.  An excellent team takes time to build and bond.  The season brings this to full circle, especially in the last few episodes where the plots begin to build toward an explosive climax in the season finale.The promise of new life with Jennifer Jareau's baby boy is a subplot.  As Jareau deals with motherhood, she faces her emotions and fears, especially as she contemplates her child and what the future may hold.Some of the best episodes are-Minimal Loss with Luke Perry; Instincts and Memoriam which features Dr. Reid's memories of a murder from his childhood, Masterpiece with Jason Alexander,  Soul Mates which gives love your neighbor a sinister twist; Roadkill which is a taut thriller with a surprise; Amplification features an analytical lecture from Reid as he is exposed to a deadly substance; and  To Hell...And Back is the season finale with enough horror, disgust and death for a whole season.  Death takes no holiday in this episode.  Unfortunately, you will never look at that Christmas ham the same way after watching this episode.This series is for mature minds.  It is definitely not for younger children.
summary: Criminal Minds: The Complete Fourth Season

reviewText: After a riveting cliff hanger for season three, "Criminal Minds" returns delivering on what was promised in the 3rd season.Hotch(Thomas Gibson) and his team tackle a variety of compelling cases including a serial rapist/murderer who mysteriously begins claiming new victims leaving his DNA behind AFTER his death ("Angel Maker")and Reid (Matthew Gaye Gublur)begins to suspect that his father may have something to do with the unsolved abduction of a boy that he played little leage with years before in Las Vegas.There have been a number of reviews suggesting that "Criminal Minds" became predictable during the 4th season. I'd disagree as I found the writers/producers willing to tackle difficult multi-part stories with unusual twists that were the equal of earlier seasons. Having watched the 4th season randomly with the second and third, I found the quality of the writing/production/acting to be as high as the previous seasons.I did find the last two episodes of the 4th season to have a great set up but I found it implausable (I don't want to spoil it for you but there were too many inconsistencies. If you PM me I'll gladly discuss them)but the conclusion did set up a nice cliffhanger for season 5 which was nicely resolved. There were a couple of episodes that also left threads hanging (for example "Demonology" never properly tied together how the death of a priest in Spain was truly tied into the three deaths in the U.S. unless I missed something)but I suspect it probably had to do with material cut for time constraints (I didn't look at the deleted scene for this episode so perhaps the info is there)and life often has loose ends. The rest of the episodes are taunt, well written and resolve the major issues nicely so one or two stumbles can be forgiven particularly on a show that is this tightly plotted.The extras include a number of featurettes including "Working the Scene" that gives us a lot of behind-the-scenes information on 11 episodes. We also get deleted scenes, profiles and a gag reel. My only other complaint is that this doesn't have subtitles (although it is close captioned so those with devices that can decode the close captioning can enjoy them)for English that you can access while watching the episodes (handy when there are distractions in the background).Recommended.
summary: Exceptional season although the two part season cliffhanger was a bit disappointing
